"{\"uid\": \"thesouthafrican.com-sport-paris-olympics-2024-olympics-athletes-sleeping-on-anti-sex-cardboard-beds\", \"text\": \"Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.  thesouthafrican.com is a division of Blue Sky Publications Ltd. Reproduction without permission prohibited  Home\\u00bbSport\\u00bbParis Olympics 2024\\u00bbOlympics: Athletes forced to sleep on 'anti-sex' cardboard beds  The sustainable anti-sex cardboard beds are being used in the Olympic Village for the 2024 Olympics in Paris.  Athletes at this year's Olympics have taken to social media to reveal the controversial single, anti-sex, high-resistance lightweight cardboard beds they have to sleep on.  With this Olympic Games around the corner and ready to kick off, all the attention has turned to the Olympic Village, where athletes are housed during the prestigious event. More specifically, the 'anti-sex' beds that are made from cardboard.  Social media is abuzz after athletes from various countries gave their millions of followers across different platforms a glimpse into their respective rooms and in particular a look at their cardboard beds.  Sevensrugbystar Libbie Janse van Rensburg, who is a member of Team South Africa at the Olympics have viewers the inside scoop: \\\"What's the deal with the beds in the Olympic Village?\\u00a0Here's the scoop,\\\" she said on TikTok.  What's the deal with the beds in the Olympic Village? Here's the scoop\\ud83d\\udc40#fyp#Olympics2024#olympicvillage#olympicbeds#cardboardeds  \\\"Just pulled up to the village and had to run it back up yall,\\\" wrote South Africa's skateboarding sensation Brandon Valjalo, who shared the video below with his social media followers.  Just pulled up to the village and had to run it back up yall!#olympics#paris2024#brandonvaljalo  \\\"Ok these beds have got out of control,\\\" wrote New Zealand swimmer Lewis Clarebut, accompanied by the video below.  Ok these beds have got out of control!#paris2024#olympics  Australian Olympic water polo player Tilly Kearns went as far as to give an in-depth review of the beds. \\\"Already had a massage to undo the damage,\\\" she said.  Already had a massage to undo the damage  Harry McNulty, the Irish sevens rugby, also gave his view on the cardboard bed saga: \\\"I have had 0 issues with the beds/sleep.\\\"  Replying to @jlh ive had 0 issues with the beds/sleep!  Australian tennis players Daria Saville and Ellen Perez also posted a video on TikTok of themselves 'testing out' the beds with a series of amusing activities, including squat jumping and doing the worm.  Testing out the cardboard beds at the Olympic Village @Ilona Maher#AllezAUS#Paris2024#Olympics#Tennis#ParisOlympics2024#ParisOlympics#olympics2024  These viral posts from athletes inside the Olympic Village sent social media into a frenzy, with many social poking fun at the cardboard beds.  \\\"These are the fittest young people in the world; sure as hell they will find a way,\\\" one person joked.  \\\"The Olympics village always looks so cheap. Tiny rooms in cramped apartments with cardboard beds and one crap open storage unit. And one bathroom between 4 rooms I doubt the likes of Nadal will be staying in the village.\\\"  \\\"Village looks cosy and calm fr. Might just join the Olympics.\\\"  Another added: \\\"Imagine thinking that a small, narrow bed is going to stop these superhumans from doing whatever they want.\\\"  \\\"Athletes uploading their cardboard beds in Paris at the Olympic village is so? what happened to Olympics budget?,\\\" quipped another person.  \\\"Do people not remember the cardboard beds for Tokyo Olympics? I am not shocked it's cardboard beds again. I will be shocked if they stop the cardboard beds, tbh.\\\"  Olympic chiefs have denied the anti-sex rumours and instead given a different reason behind the cardboard beds.  In an interview withReutersOlympic organizers said:\\u00a0\\\"We know the media has had a lot of fun with this story\\u00a0but for 2024 Paris Olympics, the choice of these beds for the Olympic & Paralympic Village is primarily linked to a wider ambition to ensure minimal environmental impact and a second life for all equipment used during the short period of the Games.\\\"  The opening ceremony of the 2024 Summer Olympics is scheduled to take place on 26 July 2024.  WIN R2 000: Take The South African's SASSA Survey  The South African is hiring! Freelance writing positions available  Follow The South African on Facebook for the latest local and international news  Follow The South African's WhatsApp channel for the latest sport, lifestyle and local news  Follow The South African on X for the latest, breaking news  A brand new shopping mall is coming to Pretoria East, bringing major retailers and new convenience to the area.  Orlando Pirates are reportedly set to welcome a new staff member in former Stellenbosch FC Head of Recruitment Brendon Fourie.  Masindi Nemtajela was stretched off during Orlando Pirates' 6-0 win over TS Galaxy on Sunday afternoon in Mbombela.  IT support is not just technical, it is personal.  Liema Pantsi's victory was clouded as fans of the 'Big Brother Mzansi' show expressed that Smash Afrika was unprofessional towards her.  A dominant weekend for the SA teams in the URC has made a big impact on the latest log standings as the playoffs edge closer.    TheSouthAfrican.com is all about South Africa and the stories that affect South Africans, wherever they are in the world.  We are independent.No agenda.No bias.  Our offices are for administrative purposes only, no visitors will be accepted without an appointment.  South Africa- Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd - Registration Number: 2005/028472/07 - Address: Regus Business Centre, 1st Floor, Block B, North Park, Black River Park, 2 Fir Street, Observatory, Cape Town, 7925, South Africa  Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.\"}"